greatest blow,
you are mistaken."

35:43.908 --> 35:49.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What are we left with? We know
most victims
don't speak out like this. What
do we -- what

35:49.514 --> 35:51.316 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
should we take away from this?

35:51.416 --> 35:55.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHELLE ANDERSON: Well, the
case is unusual
because of the extraordinary
articulateness

35:55.787 --> 36:02.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of this particular victim, and
the fact that
she used the opportunity to say
some important

36:02.527 --> 36:05.797 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
things about how rape is
experienced by its
victims.

36:05.897 --> 36:11.002 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The part of the victim's
statement that really
hit home with me and I think
with many other

36:11.102 --> 36:15.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people is the part where she
says, "I didn't
want my body anymore."

36:15.373 --> 36:25.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we know that rape and sexual
assault can
be an invasion of privacy. It
can be something

36:25.116 --> 36:30.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
